    "body": "<p>We knows about base->2 (binary) integers and base->10 (decimal) integers, and various other positive bases. But what about negative bases. OK! lets talk about the \"base-> -2\". An integer n written in base -2 is a sequence of digits written right-to-left. Each of which is either 0 or 1 (no negative digits!), and the following equality must hold:\nn = b0 + b1(-2) + b2(-2)2 + b3(-2)3 + ...\nThe cool thing is that every integer (including the negative ones) has a unique \"base-> -2\" representation, with no minus sign required. Your task is to find this representation.\n\n\n<h3>Input</h3>\n<p>The Input consists of the number of test cases. Each one is a line containing a decimal integer n, in the range from -1,000,000,000 to 1,000,000,000, excluding 0. Terminate the input with n=0.\n\n\n<h3>Output</h3>\n<p>For each test case, output one line containing base -2 representation of the input number.\n\n\n<h3>Example</h3>\n\n<pre>\n<b>Input:</b>\n1\n7\n-2\n0\n\n<b>Output:</b>\n1\n11011\n10\n</pre>\n",
